<title>SOUTH AFRICA: Haggie yr shr plunges 41 pct, div cut.</title>
<headline>Haggie yr shr plunges 41 pct, div cut.</headline>
<dateline>JOHANNESBURG 1997-02-13</dateline>
<text>
<p>Year ended December 31</p>
<p>			(million rand unless stated)</p>
<p>    Shr, headline (cts)   199	   vs   339</p>
<p>    Shr, attrib (cts)     200	   vs   302</p>
<p>    Div (cts)		 125	   vs   165</p>
<p>    Attrib income	    42.01	vs    61.17</p>
<p>    Pre-tax		    61.52	vs   101.05</p>
<p>    Tax			  15.86	vs    28.46</p>
<p>    Interest paid	    15.45	vs    18.92</p>
<p>    Turnover		1,636.04	vs 1,625.13</p>
<p>Full name: Haggie Ltd  </p>
<p>NOTE - Steel exporter Haggie said it was unable to benefit from the rand's depreciation last year as it had forward cover contracts in place for most of the year.</p>
<p>However, this position was expected to be reversed in 1997 with uncovered contracts and a weakened rand contributing to an improvement in Haggie's competitiveness against imports and in its foreign markets.</p>
<p>This combined with other factors would help greatly improve results for 1997, the company said.</p>
<p>-- Johannesburg newsroom, +27 11 482-1003</p>
